This is motivated from Twitter internal thrift cases where 1 thrift target might codegen targeting 4 languages - ruby, python, java, scala.  There is 1st the problem of representing these 4 permutations which was done at Twitter via a single macro that generated 4 targets, each owning the same source. The engine experiment has Sources as an adressable type which could solve the multiple source ownership issue, but there still remains both the issue of how to spell 4 configurations.  Could continue to be via macro, but might also be via target templates.  There is the further issue of ambiguity.  If I have a target owning java sources (a java target), and it depends on a single thrift target with all 4 configurations, both the java and scala configurations will lead to plans.  If these plans are from seperate planners, things blow up.  If from the same planner, it has to make a choice and might have no good way of doing so.  This leads into the idea of addressing specific configurations via an extension to dependency address specs, like so:
```json
{
  "type_alias": "target",
  "name": "example",
  "sources": {
    "globs": "*.java"
  },
  "dependencies": [
    "src/thrift/org/example/base@scrooge_scala
  ]
}
```

And over in `src/thrift/org/example/base/BLD.json`:
```json
{
  "type_alias": "target",
  "name": "base",
  "sources": {
    "globs": "*.thrift"
  },
  configurations = [
    {
      "type_alias": "apache_thrift_configuration",
      "name": "apache_java",
      "gen": "java",
      "rev": "0.9.2"
    },
    {
      "type_alias": "scrooge_configuration",
      "name": "scrooge_scala",
      "gen": "scala",
      "rev": "3.20.0"
    },
    ...
  ]
}
```

