**Cause:**  
Icons are confusing, user cannot directly link icon with the action (especially ‘track’);
‘Act’ and ‘Act All’ icon are the same, hard for user to understand the difference;
Three sections are not well separated;
Common user habits (try to drag file around, right click to find options, 
highlight multiple files to perform ‘Act All’);
Unfamiliar with Git based version control;

**Solution:**
Re-design action icons;
Distinguish ‘Act’ and ‘Act all’ button;
Clearly separate each section from each other (use background or outline color);
Follow common user habits:
		--add function into right click button ;
		--allow drag file across fields (challenging);

Hi,

according to the ONNX specification, it is possible for a model to have inputs with dimensions whose size is statically unknown:

> The types of the inputs and outputs of the model must be specified, including the shapes of tensors. While the ranks of input and output tensors are statically specified, the sizes of specific dimensions (axis) may be statically unknown and are indicated so using symbolic identifiers in the shape.

Unfortunately, I wasn't able to find any more information about these "symbolic identifiers". Is there any information available on how to use them?

More specifically, I have a tensor – resulting from a PyTorch export – that is supposed to serve as the input for an LSTM node. It looks like this:

```
input {
  name: "0"
  type {
    tensor_type {
      elem_type: FLOAT
      shape {
        dim {
          dim_value: 5
        }
        dim {
          dim_value: 1
        }
        dim {
          dim_value: 3
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

The first two dimensions describe sequence length and batch size, respectively, which is why it makes no sense for them to be statically specified; after all, the whole point of an RNN is to handle sequences of varying length. What I want is a tensor that looks something like this:

```
input {
  name: "0"
  type {
    tensor_type {
      elem_type: FLOAT
      shape {
        dim {
          dim_value: ?
        }
        dim {
          dim_value: ?
        }
        dim {
          dim_value: 3
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Could you give me some pointers on how to create a tensor similar to this? I have already tried `lstm_input_node.type.tensor_type.shape.dim[0].dim_value = None`, but that just results in a type error. Any help would be greatly appreciated.

